    "title": {
        "rendered": "Administration Menus"
    },
    "content": {
        "rendered": "\n<p>Administration Menus are the interfaces displayed in WordPress Administration. They allow you to add option pages for your plugin.</p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-wporg-notice is-info-notice\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-wporg-notice__icon\"></div>\n<div class=\"wp-block-wporg-notice__content\"><br />\nFor information on managing Navigation Menus, see the Navigation Menus chapter of the Theme Developer Handbook.<br />\n</div></div>\n\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Top-Level Menus and Sub-Menus</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The Top-level menus are rendered along the left side of the WordPress Administration. Each menu may contain a set of Sub-menus.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>When deciding between <a href=\"https://developer.wordpress.org/plugins/administration-menus/top-level-menus/\">Top-level menus</a> and <a href=\"https://developer.wordpress.org/plugins/administration-menus/sub-menus/\">Sub-menus</a> think carefully about the needs of your plugin as well as the needs of your end users.</p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-wporg-notice is-alert-notice\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-wporg-notice__icon\"></div>\n<div class=\"wp-block-wporg-notice__content\"><br />\nWe recommend developers with a single option page to add it as Sub-menu to one of the existing Top-level menus; such as Settings or Tools.<br />\n</div></div>\n\n",
        "protected": false
    },
